Every 10 test cycles (so roughly every day) there will be one special cycle that we'll call the peak cycle. In that cycle miner should present as many machines (currently only A6000 are supported) as they can. The test is the same as it used to be for the last few weeks.

The incentive for non-peak cycles will then be calculated as `min(peak*0.1, current)`, which means that if you are able to get your hands on 120 A6000s, you present that once a day and then for the rest of the day you are only getting paid for 12. You can present more, but it won't count. You can be paid extra for organic traffic (so if validators rent 2 machines while a non-peak cycle is running, you might be paid for 14).

The A6000 are endangered, Nvidia is not making them anymore and the supply is finite. This means that you won't need to unstake every piece of alpha that you earn to pay for the servers, because you'll bottleneck on how much good A6000s can you gather for that time of day, but you won't actually run these 24/7 so they won't cost as much... unless we do need them on some other time in which case you'll be paid extra.

1. Introduced a new term: TD (Testing Day) - equal exactly to 10 cycles (20 tempos)

Yuma 3 is a big change and it deserves scrutiny. Thank you @!      distributed_tensor [τ, γ], @CapriciousSage and @Fish | lium.io for getting up on stage to talk about the various aspects of it.

Yuma 3 is not perfect and it will get some improvements in the future for sure (three are in various stages of implementation already), however Yuma 2:
- rewards validators mainly for... being big :/
- in some cases it just issues dividends pseudo-randomly
- weight copiers love it
- it doesn't follow the paper
- it loses precision when validators and miners are small
- makes small validators ridiculously vulnerable to an attack
- makes small validators able to game the APY
- generally distributes tokens in a way that is unfair
- incentivizes poor validation
- liquid alpha 1.0 just disables itself in some subnets, doesn't work in others, sometimes works in reverse uncontrollably
- can be gamed by miner-validator colluders

Yuma 3 can also be gamed by miner-validator colluders. In some cases it might be gamed more than Yuma 2 and this risk will have to be managed. For model verification subnets it is possible to eliminate this risk completely by adding a feature to subtensor and we have the PR for it already.

🚦 **Serious-traffic readiness** — we’re getting close to being able to accept real traffic at scale. All the bigger pieces are almost ready:
- **Stake-based allowance** for validators (main focus currently — this one’s quite neat, we’ll make noise when it’s live)

- **Streaming jobs support** (long-running tasks)
- ComputeHorde SDK fallback to RunPod or validators’ own hardware

🌐 **Hordization efforts** — helping other subnets scale validation:
- Actively working on validation for **two subnets** and offloading parts of validation for **one more**
- **sn15 was hordized**, then sold 🙃 — PR's still there though, *proving it can be done*
- Talking with a few more subnets about possible integration

🧪 **Ecosystem contributions** — we're **driving Yuma3, Liquid Alpha 2.0, and further improvements**, aiming to reward high-quality validation and position ComputeHorde as a practical path to get there.
